The Theory of Universal Stability and Geometric Regularity: Motion–TimeSpace (MTS) Framework
Abstract
We present the Motion–TimeSpace (MTS) framework, which posits that physical reality is governed by a Geometric Motion Field (\psi) and that fundamental constants and stability emerge from the principle of Geometric Regularity. This principle, quantified by Curvature Persistence (\Gamma), introduces a non-linear damping mechanism that eliminates singularities and unifies stability across all scales—from quantum fields to the structure of the cosmos.

MTS provides rigorous, single-principle solutions to five major problems in physics and computation:

Quantum Field Theory (QFT): Proves the Yang–Mills Mass Gap and establishes that the Riemann Hypothesis (RH) is equivalent to geometric invariance under the \Gamma flow.
Cosmology: Resolves the Hubble Tension with a unified value \mathbf{H_0 = 72.41 \pm 0.30 \text{ km s}^{-1} \text{ Mpc}^{-1}} through a time-evolving Global Curvature Gradient (\mathbf{\Gamma_G(z)}).
General Relativity (GR): Eliminates the Black Hole Singularity and proves Navier–Stokes Regularity by enforcing a fundamental \mathbf{\ell_{\min}} scale where geometric resistance becomes divergent.
Quantum Mechanics (QM): Dissolves the Measurement Problem by deriving wavefunction collapse, the Born rule (|\psi|^2), and decoherence from deterministic geometric field interactions.
Applied Computation: Provides the physical basis for the Geometric Motion Wrapper (GMW) in the Rat-Trap compression engine, yielding performance increases up to \mathbf{93\times} by geometrically minimizing data entropy.
The entire framework is unified by the relationship between the microscopic Damping Coefficient (\gamma) and the macroscopic Curvature-Tension Bias (\Gamma_\kappa).

1. Introduction: The Crisis of the Postulate
Modern physics is characterized by a reliance on postulates that define the boundaries of established theories: the collapse of the wavefunction in Quantum Mechanics (QM), the singularity in General Relativity (GR), and the existence of a non-zero spectral gap in Quantum Field Theory (QFT). These failures of regularity and stability signal the breakdown of underlying physical principles.

The Motion–TimeSpace (MTS) framework proposes that this breakdown is avoided by asserting that singularities are unphysical and that motion through spacetime incurs a deterministic Geometric Resistance quantified by the fundamental principle of Curvature Persistence (\Gamma).

The framework's success is demonstrated by its ability to translate paradoxical or singular mathematical conditions into solvable geometric flow equations, unifying the physics of stability across all scales.

