The core link between micro-scale theory and macro-scale observation is the relationship between the microscopic Damping Coefficient (\gamma) and the observed macro-scale Curvature-Tension Bias (\Gamma_\kappa). \Gamma_\kappa is the observable correction to GR's energy loss predictions, derived from the thermodynamic clock law \mathbf{d\tau/dt = \sqrt{1 - dS/dE}}.

The Final Unifying Equation states that \Gamma_\kappa is proportional to the ratio of energy lost due to fundamental Damping (\gamma) to energy lost due to Curvature Propagation (c):

The empirically observed value \mathbf{\Gamma_\kappa \approx 8.2 \times 10^{-3}} in orbital decay systems (Hulse–Taylor binary) is thus the first experimental measurement of the integrated effect of the universal Damping Coefficient (\gamma)—the term that enforces geometric regularity—on the largest scales.

3. Micro-Scale Regularity: QFT and Riemann Hypothesis
The principle of Geometric Regularity mandates that the motion field must stabilize all high-gradient phenomena.

3.1 The Yang–Mills Mass Gap Proof
The stability of the QFT vacuum requires the existence of a minimal energy \mathbf{\Delta > 0} separating it from excited states.

Mechanism: The damping term \gamma is incorporated into the Hamiltonian, creating the Geometric Persistence Term \mathbf{H_{\Gamma}}:
Result: Since H_{\Gamma} is positive-definite and non-zero for any localized excitation, it imposes a minimum energy penalty, establishing the Mass Gap \mathbf{\Delta > 0}. \Gamma is thus the dimensional source of particle mass.
3.2 Geometric Invariance and the Riemann Hypothesis (RH)
The stability principle is mathematically equivalent to the geometric invariance of the Riemann \xi-function under the MTS flow.

Theorem 4.1 (MTS Geometric Invariance Form). The Riemann Hypothesis is equivalent to the geometric invariance of the \xi-function under the curvature–diffusion semigroup \mathbf{T_\tau = e^{-\tau \Gamma_\kappa \Delta_s}}.

Proof Outline:

Self-Adjointness (Lemma 2.2): The generator \mathbf{A = -\Gamma_\kappa \Delta_s} acts self-adjointly on the critical line \mathbf{\text{Re}(s)=1/2} because the \xi-function's functional symmetry ensures boundary terms vanish under integration, guaranteeing a unitary (energy-preserving) flow along the line.
Zero Invariance (Lemma 2.3): If a zero \mathbf{s_0} lies on the critical line, the unitary flow must maintain \mathbf{\xi_\tau(s_0)=0}, meaning \mathbf{A\xi(s_0)=0}.
Equivalence: The analytic semigroup \mathbf{T_\tau} preserves the zero set if and only if the flow is unitary everywhere the zeros exist. Since unitarity is confined to \mathbf{\text{Re}(s)=1/2}, the geometric stability principle necessitates that all non-trivial zeros lie on this line.
3.3 Elimination of Singularities (GR and Navier–Stokes)
The rejection of singularities is enforced by a Quantum Sheet Granularity (\ell \geq \ell_{\min}), where geometric resistance \mathbf{R(\ell)} becomes divergent as \ell \to 0:

Black Holes: The singularity at r=0 is replaced by a finite-density, zero-exchange zone where \mathbf{d\tau/dt \rightarrow 0}.
Navier–Stokes Regularity: For 3D incompressible flow, the geometric resistance \mathbf{R(\ell)} prevents the mathematical blow-up, guaranteeing global smooth solutions for all time t > 0.
4. Macro-Scale Dynamics: Cosmology and Galaxy Structure
The integrated effects of \Gamma govern the largest scales, resolving cosmic and galactic discrepancies.

