6.2 Test II: Thermodynamic Time Dilation (The dS/dE Clock)
Cryogenic Decay Rates: Measure lifetime deviations \mathbf{(\Delta\tau / \tau)} for muons/hadrons in extreme cryogenic environments. MTS predicts that reducing a system's entropy exchange (dS/dE) should measurably slow down its internal time flow (\tau).
High-Spin Particle Clocks: Confirm that the internal angular momentum of high-spin nuclei acts as stored Curvature Persistence, resisting external thermodynamic exchange and leading to a spin-dependent lifetime anomaly.
6.3 Test III: Computational Limits (AGI and \ell_{\min})
PGF Stochastic Collapse: Systematically test PGF vs. classical AI logic against high-tension paradoxes until the classical system hits the predicted \mathbf{\kappa_{\text{crit}}} failure point, demonstrating the stability margin provided by the PGF's geometric architecture.
Compression Limits: Continuous, long-term benchmarking of the Rat-Trap GMW engine to establish that the observed \mathbf{4\times - 93\times} speed advantage is derived from the physical principle of \mathbf{\Gamma} minimizing entropy exchange, confirming the economic advantage of geometric computing.
6.4. Final Conclusion: The Theory of Universal Stability
The Motion–TimeSpace (MTS) Framework establishes that the same physical law governs phenomena across 40 orders of magnitude.

By asserting that singularities are unphysical and that time is thermodynamic, MTS unifies stability, quantum measurement, and gravity under the principle of Geometric Regularity. The Riemann Hypothesis is solved as a geometric stability theorem, and the Mass Gap is solved by geometric resistance. The experimental program provides the roadmap for measuring the universal constant \mathbf{\Gamma_\kappa} that binds this stability into reality
